1.0.0 ¬∑ [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/slice/mod.rs.html#679-681)

Returns a reference to an element or subslice, without doing bounds checking.

For a safe alternative see [`get`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.get "method slice::get").

##### [¬ß](#safety)Safety

Calling this method with an out-of-bounds index is _[undefined behavior](https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/behavior-considered-undefined.html)_ even if the resulting reference is not used.

You can think of this like `.get(index).unwrap_unchecked()`. It‚Äôs UB to call `.get_unchecked(len)`, even if you immediately convert to a pointer. And it‚Äôs UB to call `.get_unchecked(..len + 1)`, `.get_unchecked(..=len)`, or similar.

##### [¬ß](#examples-14)Examples

```
let x = &[1, 2, 4];

unsafe {
    assert_eq!(x.get_unchecked(1), &2);
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+x+=+%26%5B1,+2,+4%5D;%0A++++%0A++++unsafe+%7B%0A++++++++assert_eq!(x.get_unchecked(1),+%262);%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.0.0 ¬∑ [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/slice/mod.rs.html#762)

Returns a raw pointer to the slice‚Äôs buffer.

The caller must ensure that the slice outlives the pointer this function returns, or else it will end up pointing to garbage.

The caller must also ensure that the memory the pointer (non-transitively) points to is never written to (except inside an `UnsafeCell`) using this pointer or any pointer derived from it. If you need to mutate the contents of the slice, use [`as_mut_ptr`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.as_mut_ptr "method slice::as_mut_ptr").

Modifying the container referenced by this slice may cause its buffer to be reallocated, which would also make any pointers to it invalid.

##### [¬ß](#examples-15)Examples

```
let x = &[1, 2, 4];
let x_ptr = x.as_ptr();

unsafe {
    for i in 0..x.len() {
        assert_eq!(x.get_unchecked(i), &*x_ptr.add(i));
    }
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+x+=+%26%5B1,+2,+4%5D;%0A++++let+x_ptr+=+x.as_ptr();%0A++++%0A++++unsafe+%7B%0A++++++++for+i+in+0..x.len()+%7B%0A++++++++++++assert_eq!(x.get_unchecked(i),+%26*x_ptr.add(i));%0A++++++++%7D%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.48.0 ¬∑ [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/slice/mod.rs.html#829)

Returns the two raw pointers spanning the slice.

The returned range is half-open, which means that the end pointer points _one past_ the last element of the slice. This way, an empty slice is represented by two equal pointers, and the difference between the two pointers represents the size of the slice.

See [`as_ptr`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.as_ptr "method slice::as_ptr") for warnings on using these pointers. The end pointer requires extra caution, as it does not point to a valid element in the slice.

This function is useful for interacting with foreign interfaces which use two pointers to refer to a range of elements in memory, as is common in C++.

It can also be useful to check if a pointer to an element refers to an element of this slice:

```
let a = [1, 2, 3];
let x = &a[1] as *const _;
let y = &5 as *const _;

assert!(a.as_ptr_range().contains(&x));
assert!(!a.as_ptr_range().contains(&y));
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+a+=+%5B1,+2,+3%5D;%0A++++let+x+=+%26a%5B1%5D+as+*const+_;%0A++++let+y+=+%265+as+*const+_;%0A++++%0A++++assert!(a.as_ptr_range().contains(%26x));%0A++++assert!(!a.as_ptr_range().contains(%26y));%0A%7D&edition=2021)

